From: "Jason Rogers" <jason.rogers@...>

 
    > This doesn't test whether or not the Enumerations are 
    > iterating over the
    > same collection... thus, your next point.
    > 
    >     > You can test the value of each element of the Collection 
    >     > or Enumeration.
    >     > 
    >     >   //loop over enumeration
    >     >   SomeClass sc = (SomeClass) enumeration.nextElement();
    >     >   assertEquals(some_value, sc.getSomeValue());
    > 
    > However, if you don't have a Comparator for these 
    > objects, the equals()
    > method will test that they are the same object in memory, 
    > which will
    > invariably cause the test to fail.  So, if these objects 
    > are your own
    > objects, you can override the equals() method on the 
    > object.  If they are
    > not your own you have to write a Comparator for them (or something
    > equivalent).

To follow up on my own post... You could have your object implement
Comparable and write the compareTo() method, or the Comparator and write the
compare() and equals() methods.
subject: RE: [junit] How to test a bussiness method returns a enumeration
